<body>

<h1>@HI{{toka}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong> is used to list example nouns in the same way that <a href="grammar-particle-ya.html">@HI{{ya}}</a> is used.
However, <strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>
is more informal. Furthermore, <strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong> can sometimes follow the last noun listed, which @HI{{ya}}
never can.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{donnna @KT{{supo-tsu}}wo shite imasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{sou desune. @KT{{tenisu}}<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong> @KJ{{water^swim}}<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>...}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: What kind of sports do you do?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Well ... playing tennis, swimming and so on.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong> can follow  pairs of words of opposite meaning to indicate uncertainty.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}hasonotokiniyotte,@KJ{{attend^matter}}ga@KJ{{mask^white}}i<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>
      @KJ{{mask^white}}kunai<strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong>@KJ{{say}}unode,dochiranokawakarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Depending on which day it is, she says she likes here work or she doesn't like it, so I don't know whether she does or not.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When used with nouns <strong>@HI{{toka}}</strong> has a more informal feel than @HI{{ya}}.
</p>


